        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "import glob\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "from scipy.stats import yeojohnson,boxcox\n",
        "\n",
        "klasor_yolu = '/content/drive/MyDrive/case/data/'\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "dosya_listesi = sorted(glob.glob(klasor_yolu + '*.csv'))\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "for index, dosya_yolu in enumerate(dosya_listesi, start=0):\n",
        "    veri = pd.read_csv(dosya_yolu)\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "    isim = f\"data{index}\"\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "    globals()[isim] = veri\n",
        "\n",
        "    print(f\"{isim} başarıyla yüklendi: {dosya_yolu}\")"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "background_save": true
        },
        "id": "rZUyr1e4XK3f"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "full_df = pd.concat([\n",
        "    data0, data1, data2, data3, data4, data5, data6,\n",
        "    data7, data8, data9, data10, data11, data12,\n",
        "    data13, data14, data15, data16\n",
        "])\n",
        "\n",
        "full_df[\"event_date\"] = pd.to_datetime(full_df[\"event_date\"], errors=\"coerce\")\n",
        "full_df[\"install_date\"] = pd.to_datetime(full_df[\"install_date\"], errors=\"coerce\")\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## Note on Data Merging and Temporal Dimension\n",
        "\n",
        "At this stage, datasets from different time periods have been merged into a single event-level table.  \n",
        "This approach:\n",
        "\n",
        "- improves comparability across periods,  \n",
        "- enables feature engineering from a unified data source,  \n",
        "- requires that the train–test split in later stages be **time-based** to avoid data leakage.\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "TB6FF9vUnBMo"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "background_save": true
        },
        "id": "nYzFtCVSd7Pd"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "user_level = (\n",
        "    full_df\n",
        "    .groupby(\"user_id\")\n",
        "    .agg(\n",
        "        country = (\"country\", \"first\"),\n",
        "        install_date = (\"install_date\", \"first\"),\n",
        "        platform = (\"platform\", \"first\"),\n",
        "\n",
        "        total_session_count = (\"total_session_count\", \"sum\"),\n",
        "        total_session_duration = (\"total_session_duration\", \"sum\"),\n",
        "        match_start_count = (\"match_start_count\", \"sum\"),\n",
        "        match_end_count = (\"match_end_count\", \"sum\"),\n",
        "        victory_count = (\"victory_count\", \"sum\"),\n",
        "        defeat_count = (\"defeat_count\", \"sum\"),\n",
        "        server_connection_error = (\"server_connection_error\", \"sum\"),\n",
        "        iap_revenue = (\"iap_revenue\", \"sum\"),\n",
        "        ad_revenue = (\"ad_revenue\", \"sum\")\n",
        "    )\n",
        "    .reset_index()\n",
        ")\n",
        "user_level[\"win_rate\"] = (\n",
        "    user_level[\"victory_count\"] /\n",
        "    user_level[\"match_start_count\"].replace(0, 1)\n",
        ")"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## Comment on Aggregation Strategy\n",
        "\n",
        "In this step, event-level data has been aggregated to a user-level representation.\n",
        "\n",
        "Using `sum` for behavioral metrics is justified because:\n",
        "\n",
        "- users who stay longer on the platform tend to generate higher activity,  \n",
        "- cumulative behavior is strongly related to outcomes such as churn or LTV,  \n",
        "- aggregated features are more suitable for scalable modeling.\n",
        "\n",
        "For static variables (`country`, `platform`, `install_date`), the use of `first` assumes that these attributes remain stable over time.\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "QFV65RA9nHor"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## Note on Win Rate Metric\n",
        "\n",
        "Win rate serves as a key behavioral indicator of user performance.\n",
        "\n",
        "This variable may be correlated with:\n",
        "\n",
        "- user skill level,  \n",
        "- engagement intensity,  \n",
        "- likelihood of retention,\n",
        "\n",
        "and therefore can be an important predictor in downstream models.\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "JuFk0r7bnXSo"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {
        "id": "n2V2XuNvd71F",

This behavior is deprecated, and in a future version of pandas the grouping columns will be excluded from the operation. Either pass `include_groups=False` to exclude the groupings or explicitly select the grouping columns after groupby to silence this warning.\n",
            "  .apply(avg_gap_including_start)\n"

          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "user_id\n",
            "1000038539402B14      0.000000\n",
            "10001B26D923438D    554.000000\n",
            "10001BC582D7177       0.000000\n",
            "10001C7BB5E78FD2     13.200000\n",
            "10001E40A06E1D93    298.000000\n",
            "                       ...    \n",
            "FFFFD89FB0A72825      4.714286\n",
            "FFFFE1B570BC1AE5     11.500000\n",
            "FFFFEA9652DE3B36      0.500000\n",
            "FFFFEB2E54B8F7B7    191.500000\n",
            "FFFFF421923FB03B      0.000000\n",
            "Name: avg_days_between_visits_incl_start, Length: 2453499, dtype: float64\n"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "user_level[\"last_active_day\"] = (\n",
        "    full_df.groupby(\"user_id\")[\"event_date\"].max().values\n",
        ")\n",
        "user_level[\"days_since_last_active\"] = (\n",
        "    full_df[\"event_date\"].max() - user_level[\"last_active_day\"]\n",
        ").dt.days\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "u = (\n",
        "    full_df[[\"user_id\", \"event_date\", \"install_date\"]]\n",
        "    .drop_duplicates([\"user_id\", \"event_date\"])\n",
        "    .sort_values([\"user_id\", \"event_date\"])\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "def avg_gap_including_start(g):\n",
        "    start = g[\"install_date\"].iloc[0]\n",
        "    dates = g[\"event_date\"].to_numpy()\n",
        "\n",
        "    gaps = []\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "    gaps.append(int((dates[0] - start) / np.timedelta64(1, \"D\")))\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "    if len(dates) > 1:\n",
        "        diffs = np.diff(dates)\n",
        "        gaps.extend([int(d / np.timedelta64(1, \"D\")) for d in diffs])\n",
        "\n",
        "    return float(np.mean(gaps))\n",
        "\n",
        "avg_gap = (\n",
        "    u.groupby(\"user_id\", group_keys=False)\n",
        "     .apply(avg_gap_including_start)\n",
        "     .rename(\"avg_days_between_visits_incl_start\")\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "print(avg_gap)\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "user_level = user_level.merge(\n",
        "    avg_gap,\n",
        "    left_on=\"user_id\",\n",
        "    right_index=True,\n",
        "    how=\"left\"\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "user_level[\"total_logins_sessions\"] = full_df.groupby(\"user_id\")[\"total_session_count\"].sum().values\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## Recency Dimension\n",
        "\n",
        "`days_since_last_active` represents the **Recency** component in the classical RFM framework.\n",
        "\n",
        "Typically:\n",
        "\n",
        "- higher values → higher churn risk,  \n",
        "- lower values → stronger engagement.\n",
        "\n",
        "This feature is often among the most critical predictors in churn modeling.\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "7vkpSmuInjsG"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## Inter-Visit Gap Metric\n",
        "\n",
        "This function measures how frequently users return to the platform.\n",
        "\n",
        "Interpretation:\n",
        "\n",
        "- high average gap → irregular user, potentially higher churn risk,  \n",
        "- low average gap → frequent user, stronger engagement.\n",
        "\n",
        "Including the gap from install date to first event allows the metric to capture early user behavior as well.\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "oU7ePUmXn8HJ"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [

      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "from scipy.stats import yeojohnson, boxcox\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "for col in user_level.select_dtypes(include=['int', 'float']).columns:\n",
        "\n",
        "    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 5, figsize=(35, 6))\n",
        "    ax1, ax2, ax3, ax4, ax5 = axes  # 5 eksen\n",
        "\n",
        "    # --- ORIGINAL ---\n",
        "    user_level[col].hist(ax=ax1)\n",
        "    ax1.set_title(f\"{col} - Orijinal\")\n",
        "\n",
        "    # --- LOG ---\n",
        "    np.log1p(user_level[col].clip(lower=0)).hist(ax=ax2)\n",
        "    ax2.set_title(f\"{col} - Log1p\")\n",
        "\n",
        "    # --- SQRT ---\n",
        "    np.sqrt(user_level[col].clip(lower=0)).hist(ax=ax3)\n",
        "    ax3.set_title(f\"{col} - Sqrt\")\n",
        "\n",
        "    # --- YEO-JOHNSON ---\n",
        "    yj_transformed = yeojohnson(user_level[col])[0]\n",
        "    pd.Series(yj_transformed).hist(ax=ax4)\n",
        "    ax4.set_title(f\"{col} - Yeo-Johnson\")\n",
        "\n",
        "    # --- BOX-COX\n",
        "    col_positive = user_level[col].copy()\n",
        "\n",
        "    if col_positive.min() <= 0:\n",
        "        col_positive = col_positive - col_positive.min() + 1  # pozitif yap\n",
        "\n",
        "    bc_transformed, lam = boxcox(col_positive)\n",
        "\n",
        "    pd.Series(bc_transformed).hist(ax=ax5)\n",
        "    ax5.set_title(f\"{col} - Box-Cox (λ={round(lam,2)})\")\n",
        "\n",
        "    plt.tight_layout()\n",
        "    plt.show()\n"
      ],

    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "from scipy.stats import yeojohnson\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "df_processed = pd.DataFrame(index=user_level.index)\n",
        "\n",
        "# ---------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "# 1. STRATEGY: BINNING (For Zero-Inflated variables)\n",
        "# ---------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "# Variables with too many zeros where distribution doesn't spread well with transforms\n",
        "def apply_custom_binning(series):\n",
        "    # Logic: 0 for zero, 1 for low (below median), 2 for high (above median)\n",
        "    non_zero = series[series > 0]\n",
        "    if non_zero.empty:\n",
        "        return series\n",
        "\n",
        "    threshold = non_zero.median()\n",
        "    # bins: [-inf, 0, median, inf] -> results in discrete categories [0, 1, 2]\n",
        "    return pd.cut(series, bins=[-np.inf, 0, threshold, np.inf], labels=[0, 1, 2]).astype(int)\n",
        "\n",
        "bin_cols = ['iap_revenue', 'ad_revenue', 'server_connection_error']\n",
        "for col in bin_cols:\n",
        "    if col in user_level.columns:\n",
        "        df_processed[col] = apply_custom_binning(user_level[col])\n",
        "\n",
        "# ---------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "# 2. STRATEGY: YEO-JOHNSON (For Skewed Count/Time variables)\n",
        "# ---------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "# Best for making skewed distributions more Gaussian (Normal)\n",
        "yj_cols = [\n",
        "    'match_end_count',\n",
        "    'victory_count',\n",
        "    'defeat_count',\n",
        "    'avg_days_between_visits_incl_start'\n",
        "]\n",
        "for col in yj_cols:\n",
        "    if col in user_level.columns:\n",
        "        # yeojohnson handles 0 values unlike standard Box-Cox\n",
        "        df_processed[col], _ = yeojohnson(user_level[col])\n",
        "\n",
        "# ---------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "# 3. STRATEGY: LOG1P (For Engagement/Duration variables)\n",
        "# ---------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "# Standard log transform for session metrics\n",
        "log_cols = ['total_logins_sessions', 'total_session_duration']\n",
        "for col in log_cols:\n",
        "    if col in user_level.columns:\n",
        "        df_processed[col] = np.log1p(user_level[col].clip(lower=0))\n",
        "\n",
        "# ---------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "# 4. STRATEGY: ORIGINAL\n",
        "# ---------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "# For variables that are already well-distributed or are ratios (0-1)\n",
        "original_cols = ['days_since_last_active', 'win_rate']\n",
        "for col in original_cols:\n",
        "    if col in user_level.columns:\n",
        "        df_processed[col] = user_level[col]\n",
        "\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "OBZ7v7i7VaUR"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "###Feature Transformation Rationale for PCA & Clustering\n",
        "\n",
        "I have applied specific transformations to each feature to ensure the data is mathematically suitable for Principal Component Analysis (PCA) and subsequent Clustering.<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "**1. Monetization & Error Metrics (Custom Binning)**<br>\n",
        "**Features:** *iap_revenue, ad_revenue, server_connection_error*<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "**Transformation:** Custom Binning (0: None, 1: Low, 2: High)<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "**Rationale:** These features are highly zero-inflated (over 95% zeros). Standard mathematical transforms (like Log) cannot normalize such extreme spikes. Categorizing them captures the structural difference between \"Payers\" and \"Non-Payers\" while preventing extreme \"Whale\" outliers from distorting the model.<br>\n",
        "**2. Activity & Engagement Counts (Yeo-Johnson)**<br>\n",
        "**Features:** * match_end_count, victory_count, defeat_count, avg_days_between_visits_incl_start*<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "**Transformation:** Yeo-Johnson Transform<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "**Rationale:** These follow a Power Law distribution (many low-activity players, few high-activity players). Unlike Box-Cox, Yeo-Johnson supports zero values. It spreads the distribution to be more Gaussian-like, allowing PCA to identify variance across the entire player base rather than just focusing on extreme outliers.<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "**3. Session Intensity (Log1p)**<br>\n",
        "**Features:** *total_logins_sessions, total_session_duration*<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "**Transformation:** Log1p (log(1+x))<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "Rationale: Engagement metrics typically grow exponentially. Log1p compresses the scale of long-tailed engagement data, making the relative differences between casual and power users more comparable for the clustering algorithm.<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "**4. Performance & Recency (Original Scale)**<br>\n",
        "**Features:** *win_rate, days_since_last_active*<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "Transformation: None (Original)<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "Rationale: win_rate is already naturally bounded (0 to 1). days_since_last_active represents a linear decay of interest (churn risk). Transforming these would destroy their inherent physical meaning, which PCA can already interpret linearly.<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "**5. Final Pre-processing (StandardScaler)**<br>\n",
        "**Transformation:** *Z-Score Normalization*<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "Rationale: PCA is a variance-maximizing algorithm and is sensitive to the scale of the data. Standardizing ensures that features with large raw values (like duration in seconds) do not mathematically dominate features with small values (like win rate)."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "gqgH3KGHXyFf"
      }
    },

        "####**Engagement drives everything:**\n",
        "Longer playtime is strongly associated with more sessions and more matches, indicating that total session duration is the core indicator of user engagement.\n",
        "\n",
        "####**Match metrics are redundant:**\n",
        "Match start, match end, and victories are highly correlated, suggesting that one representative metric could be sufficient in analysis or modeling.\n",
        "\n",
        "####**Ad revenue follows activity, not willingness to pay:**\n",
        "Higher ad revenue is mainly explained by higher play intensity rather than user quality or loyalty.\n",
        "\n",
        "####**IAP reflects a different user behavior:**\n",
        "In-app purchase revenue shows weak correlation with gameplay metrics, implying that paying users form a distinct and small segment.\n",
        "\n",
        "####**Days since last active is a meaningful churn signal:**\n",
        "Users with lower engagement tend to have higher days_since_last_active, confirming this metric as a reliable indicator of churn risk."
      ]

        "# ===============================\n",
        "# 4) PCA\n",
        "# ===============================\n",
        "from sklearn.decomposition import PCA\n",
        "\n",
        "pca = PCA(n_components=4, random_state=42)\n",
        "X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_final)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Bileşen bazında varyans:\", pca.explained_variance_ratio_)\n",
        "print(\"Toplam açıklanan varyans (4 komponent):\", pca.explained_variance_ratio_.sum())\n",
        "\n",
        "loadings = pd.DataFrame(\n",
        "    pca.components_.T,\n",
        "    index=X_final.columns,\n",
        "    columns=[\"PC1\", \"PC2\", \"PC3\", \"PC4\"]\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "# PCA skorlarını user_level'a yaz\n",
        "user_level[[\"PC1\",\"PC2\",\"PC3\",\"PC4\"]] = X_pca\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "# 3) Tüm bileşenleri otomatik çiz\n",
        "for pc in [\"PC1\", \"PC2\", \"PC3\", \"PC4\"]:\n",
        "    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))\n",
        "    loadings[pc].sort_values().plot(kind=\"bar\")\n",
        "    plt.title(f\"PCA Loadings - {pc}\")\n",
        "    plt.ylabel(\"Loading value\")\n",
        "    plt.tight_layout()\n",
        "    plt.show()"

    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "BjvBaOBcKxnj"
      },
      "source": [
        "**PC1 — Standardized Gameplay Engagement**<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "PC1 represents standardized overall gameplay engagement and intensity.\n",
        "It is driven jointly by session frequency and match activity (starts, ends, wins, and losses), capturing how actively a user plays relative to the population.<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "**PC2 — Standardized Recency / Churn Risk**<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "PC2 captures standardized user recency and potential churn risk.\n",
        "It is largely driven by days_since_last_active, distinguishing recently active users from those inactive for longer periods, with a secondary association to server issues.<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "**PC3 — Technical Friction (Independent Error Dimension)**<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "PC3 isolates technical friction as a largely independent behavioral dimension.\n",
        "It is almost entirely driven by standardized server_connection_error, indicating that technical problems form a separate axis from engagement or recency.<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "**PC4 — Playstyle Trade-off: Efficiency vs Volume (Standardized)**<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "PC4 differentiates win-oriented players from high-volume session players.\n",
        "It contrasts standardized victory_count against total session activity and logins, separating efficient winners from users who generate activity mainly through sheer play volume."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {
        "id": "GhmgRUFYANHT"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "# ===============================\n",
        "# 5) KMeans\n",
        "# ===============================\n",
        "from sklearn.cluster import KMeans\n",
        "\n",
        "kmeans4 = KMeans(n_clusters=4, random_state=42, n_init=\"auto\")\n",
        "user_level[\"segment4\"] = kmeans4.fit_predict(X_pca)\n",
        "\n",
        "# ===============================\n",
        "# 6) ÇIKTI: user_id + segment\n",
        "# ===============================\n",
        "user_segments = user_level[[id_col, \"segment4\", \"PC1\", \"PC2\", \"PC3\", \"PC4\"]].copy()\n",
        "# İstersen sadece id+segment:\n",
        "# user_segments = user_level[[id_col, \"segment4\"]].copy()\n"
      ]

      "source": [
        "# ===============================\n",
        "# 7) Driver analizi (HATA DÜZELTİLMİŞ HALİ)\n",
        "# ===============================\n",
        "# Segment bazlı feature ortalaması (X_final ölçeğinde)\n",
        "profile_scaled = (\n",
        "    X_final\n",
        "    .assign(segment=user_level[\"segment4\"].values)\n",
        "    .groupby(\"segment\")\n",
        "    .mean()\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Genel ortalama (kolon isimleri aynı olacak şekilde!)\n",
        "overall_mean = X_final.mean()\n",
        "\n",
        "# Hizalı çıkarma (en sık hata burada olur)\n",
        "delta = profile_scaled.sub(overall_mean, axis=1)\n",
        "\n",
        "top_drivers = {}\n",
        "for s in delta.index:\n",
        "    top = delta.loc[s].abs().sort_values(ascending=False).head(6)\n",
        "    top_drivers[s] = pd.DataFrame({\n",
        "        \"feature\": top.index,\n",
        "        \"delta_from_mean\": delta.loc[s, top.index].values\n",
        "    })\n",
        "    print(f\"\\n--- Segment {s} top drivers ---\")\n",
        "    print(top_drivers[s])"
      ]
    },

            "\n",
            "          days_since_last_active  total_logins_sessions  platform_ios  \n",
            "segment4                                                               \n",
            "0                         12.715                  3.000         0.317  \n",
            "1                          0.173                142.232         0.359  \n",
            "2                          1.935                 41.823         0.415  \n",
            "3                          0.394                 94.796         0.404  \n",
            "\n",
            "===== PCA PROFILE BY SEGMENT =====\n",
            "             PC1    PC2    PC3    PC4\n",
            "segment4                             \n",
            "0         -0.355  0.012 -0.003  0.038\n",
            "1         37.076  5.011 -1.118  9.097\n",
            "2          5.278 -0.658  0.262 -1.070\n",
            "3         15.491  0.289 -0.404 -1.420\n"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "\n",
        "# ===============================\n",
        "# 1) Segment bazlı HAM feature ortalamaları\n",
        "# ===============================\n",
        "\n",
        "# Combine original numerical columns from user_level with the one-hot encoded categorical columns from X_cat\n",
        "# The index of X_cat and user_level should align, which they do as X_cat was created from user_level.\n",
        "raw_features_for_profiling = pd.concat([user_level[num_cols], X_cat], axis=1)\n",
        "\n",
        "raw_profile = (\n",
        "    raw_features_for_profiling\n",
        "    .assign(segment4=user_level[\"segment4\"]) # Add segment information from user_level\n",
        "    .groupby(\"segment4\")\n",
        "    .mean()\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"\\n===== RAW FEATURE PROFILE BY SEGMENT =====\")\n",
        "print(raw_profile.round(3))\n",
        "\n",
        "# ===============================\n",
        "# 2) Segment bazlı PCA skor ortalamaları\n",
        "# ===============================\n",
        "pca_cols = [\"PC1\", \"PC2\", \"PC3\", \"PC4\"]\n",
        "\n",
        "pca_profile = (\n",
        "    user_level\n",
        "    .groupby(\"segment4\")[pca_cols]\n",
        "    .mean()\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"\\n===== PCA PROFILE BY SEGMENT =====\")\n",
        "print(pca_profile.round(3))"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "PcU-X2IXKRai"
      },
      "source": [
        "# Segment Analysis – Summary Interpretation\n",
        "\n",
        "The following assessment is based on the joint interpretation of **raw feature averages** and **PCA component averages** across segments.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## **Segment 1 — Super Heavy / Power Players (Core Users)**  \n",
        "\n",
        "**Observations:**\n",
        "- Very high session frequency and match activity (average 142 sessions).\n",
        "- Highest number of victories and overall gameplay intensity.\n",
        "- Average **days_since_last_active = 0.17**, indicating near-daily activity.\n",
        "- Highest level of server connection errors, likely a by-product of heavy usage.\n",
        "- **PC1 is extremely high**, confirming strong engagement.\n",
        "- **PC4 is positive and high**, indicating an efficient, win-oriented playstyle.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Interpretation:**  \n",
        "This segment represents the most loyal and valuable core users of the game. They generate the majority of in-game activity, but their intensive usage also exposes them to more technical issues.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Recommendations:**\n",
        "- Prioritize server performance and stability for this group.\n",
        "- Consider VIP benefits, exclusive rewards, or loyalty programs.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## **Segment 3 — Heavy but Less Efficient Players**\n",
        "\n",
        "**Observations:**\n",
        "- High gameplay volume (average 94 sessions), but lower efficiency compared to Segment 1.\n",
        "- Regular activity (**days_since_last_active = 0.39**).\n",
        "- Moderate level of server errors.\n",
        "- **PC1 is high**, but **PC4 is negative**, suggesting high activity but lower win efficiency.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Interpretation:**  \n",
        "This group consists of highly active players who play a lot but do not convert their activity into wins as efficiently as Segment 1.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Recommendations:**\n",
        "- Improve matchmaking systems.\n",
        "- Provide skill-building tutorials or guidance.\n",
        "- Introduce game mechanics that support win-rate improvement.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## **Segment 2 — Mid-Core / Regular Players**\n",
        "\n",
        "**Observations:**\n",
        "- Moderate activity level (average 42 sessions).\n",
        "- Reasonable number of matches and victories.\n",
        "- Average **days_since_last_active = 1.93**, indicating intermittent but consistent return behavior.\n",
        "- Low server error rates.\n",
        "- **PC1 is moderate**, **PC2 is negative** (relatively regular return), and **PC3 is low** (few technical issues).\n",
        "\n",
        "**Interpretation:**  \n",
        "This segment represents regular but not hardcore players. Their behavior is relatively stable and they experience few technical problems.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Recommendations:**\n",
        "- Use light promotions and push notifications to increase engagement.\n",
        "- Implement retention-focused incentives to grow this segment.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## **Segment 0 — Casual / At-Risk Players**\n",
        "\n",
        "**Observations:**\n",
        "- Very low activity (average 3 sessions).\n",
        "- Low number of matches and victories.\n",
        "- **days_since_last_active = 12.7**, indicating long inactivity periods.\n",
        "- Minimal server issues.\n",
        "- **PC1 is negative**, confirming low engagement.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Interpretation:**  \n",
        "This group consists of casual players who rarely play and are at high risk of churn.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Recommendations:**\n",
        "- Launch re-engagement campaigns.\n",
        "- Offer “welcome back” bonuses.\n",
        "- Simplify onboarding and early-game experience.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## **Overall Conclusion**\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Segment 1:** Core, highly engaged and most valuable players.  \n",
        "- **Segment 3:** High-volume players with room to improve efficiency.  \n",
        "- **Segment 2:** Regular players with growth potential.  \n",
        "- **Segment 0:** Casual players with high churn risk.\n",
        "\n",
        "This segmentation provides actionable insights for both product development and marketing strategy.\n"
      ]
